  "output": "The task's framing (N+1 queries, React re-renders, caching) is templated for a different kind of app — `apps/cli` is actually a **524-line Go TUI** (Bubble Tea) that shells out to the Python crawler, with no database and no React. Here's what those categories map to in this actual codebase, with line refs.\n\n## 1. Redundant O(n) rescan on every render (the \"unnecessary re-render\" equivalent)\n\n`viewRunning()` calls `articlesSaved(st.lines)` for **every provider, on every `View()` call** — and Bubble Tea calls `View()` after every message, including every `spinner.TickMsg` (~10/sec) and every single stdout line from every crawler.\n\n```go\n// tui.go:360-368 — rescans the full slice from scratch each time\nfunc articlesSaved(lines []string) int {\n\tn := 0\n\tfor _, l := range lines {\n\t\tif strings.HasPrefix(l, \"  - \") {\n\t\t\tn++\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn n\n}\n```\n\nFor N providers with L accumulated lines, that's O(N×L) prefix-scans repeated many times per second, growing worse the longer an unlimited (`--limit 0`) run goes.\n\n**Fix** — track the count incrementally where the line arrives:\n\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate   providerState\n\tlines   []string\n\tsavedCt int // increment in-place instead of rescanning\n}\n\n// in Update(), statusMsg case (tui.go:107-114):\ncase statusMsg:\n\tst := m.statuses[msg.provider]\n\tst.state = stateRunning\n\tst.lines = append(st.lines, msg.line)\n\tif strings.HasPrefix(msg.line, \"  - \") {\n\t\tst.savedCt++\n\t}\n\t...\n```\n\n## 2. Unbounded memory growth of log history\n\n`providerStatus.lines` (tui.go:36) appends every stdout line forever with no cap. For `--limit 0` against a provider that returns thousands of matches, this grows without bound, and `refreshViewport` rebuilds the entire string via `strings.Join` on **every** update to the highlighted provider (tui.go:250):\n\n```go\nfunc (m *model) refreshViewport() {\n\t...\n\tm.vp.SetContent(strings.Join(m.statuses[name].lines, \"\\n\")) // full rejoin each call\n\tm.vp.GotoBottom()\n}\n```\n\n**Fix**: cap retained lines to a bounded tail (e.g., last 500) for display, and keep the article count separately (per fix #1) so trimming display history doesn't lose the count.\n\n## 3. No concurrency cap on process spawns (the closest thing to \"N+1\" here)\n\nBoth `runHeadless` (main.go:80-95) and `startRun` (tui.go:254-274) launch one `uv run main.py <provider>` OS subprocess **per selected provider, with no limit**. `--providers all` means 11 concurrent Python interpreter + scrapling/browser-automation processes at once — this is the resource-explosion analogue of N+1.\n\n**Fix**: bound concurrency with a semaphore:\n\n```go\nsem := make(chan struct{}, 4) // tune to CPU/network budget\nfor _, name := range names {\n\twg.Add(1)\n\tgo func(name string) {\n\t\tdefer wg.Done()\n\t\tsem <- struct{}{}\n\t\tdefer func() { <-sem }()\n\t\trunCrawler(name, limit, crawlerDir, ...)\n\t}(name)\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Minor dead code\n\n`name := name` (tui.go:266) is a pre-Go-1.22 loop-variable-capture workaround. `go.mod` requires `go 1.26.1`, where loop variables are per-iteration by default — this line is now a no-op and can be deleted.\n\n---\n\nNo genuine caching opportunities exist here (nothing is fetched/computed repeatedly from an external source inside this Go binary — that logic lives in the Python crawler, which is out of scope for `apps/cli`). If you'd like, I can run the same analysis against `apps/crawler` (Python), where the N+1/caching framing is more likely to actually apply given it's doing HTTP scraping and persistence.\n",
